com.ibm.team.repository.common.query

Interface IQueryGenerationOptions


  • public interface IQueryGenerationOptions
    Provides support for passing a small set of options to the SQL generator.

    Pattern Replacements

    The following pattern replacements are supported for setOracleHints(String...) and setDb2OptimizationGuidelines(String...):
    • {table logicalTableName} - This is replaced with the alias that will be used in the query for the specified table. The logicalTableName is optional; if it is omitted then the query's root table will be used (which is the typical case).
    • {index logicalTableName logicalIndexName} - This is replaced with the name of the specified index on the specified table. The logicalTableName is optional; if it is omitted then the query's root table will be used (which is the typical case).
    • {index logicalTableName (logicalColumnName ...)} - This is replaced with the name of the index on the specified table and columns. The logicalTableName is optional; if it is omitted then the query's root table will be used (which is the typical case).

    Limitations: For non-tribial queries it may not be possible to simply use the replacements provided above and you might have to resort to inspecting the SQL generated for a particular query and crafting a more verbatim set of optimization guidelines that do not use replacements. This limitation is inherent because there isn't a way at the query model level to address particular tables or aliases that may be used in the SQL generated from the query.

    Note: If any of the provided Oracle hints or DB2 optimization guidelines contain an invalid replacement then IllegalArgumentException will be thrown during SQL generation when the query is to be executed.

    See Also:
    IQuery.setQueryGenerationOptions(IQueryGenerationOptions)

    • Method Detail

      • setOracleHints

        void setOracleHints(java.lang.String... oracleHints)
        Note:
        • This method applies only when running on Oracle. On other DBs, Oracle hints are ignored and have no effect.
        • Before you use this method you should be very sure that the hint(s) you provide will improve performance in all situations likely to be encountered in the field. By using this method you are essentially telling Oracle to ignore what it would have chosen as the best execution plan for the query. It is quite possible to provide a hint that makes performance significantly worse.
        • For reference, see the Hints section in the Oracle Database SQL Language Reference.

        If Oracle hints are set then, during query generation, they are included (separated by a space) at the appropriate place in the generated SQL as an Oracle hint comment ("/*+ ... */"). Each hint is included after performing any pattern replacements it may include. (See Pattern Replacements in the class description.)

        Examples (using modeled types from com.ibm.team.repository.tests.common/models/RepositoryTestModel.ecore):

        • The following results in hint "/*+ index(t1 TESTS_TEAM_SEVERITY) */":
          •  LogProblemQueryModel logProblemModel = LogProblemQueryModel.ROOT;
 IDataQuery logProblemQuery = IDataQuery.FACTORY.newInstance(logProblemModel);
 ⋮
 logProblemQuery.getQueryGenerationOptions().setOracleHints("index({table} {index ( teamResponsible.itemId severity )})");
        • The following results in hint "/*+ index(t2 TESTS_TESTS_LOG_LOG_ENTRIES) */":
          •  LogQueryModel logModel = LogQueryModel.ROOT; AstQuery logQuery = (AstQuery) IDataQuery.FACTORY.newInstance(logModel);
 logQuery.select(logModel.name(), logModel.logEntries().who().name());
 ⋮
 logQuery.getQueryGenerationOptions().setOracleHints("index({table logEntries} {index logEntries (who.itemId time)})");
        • The following results in hint "/*+ index(t1 TESTS_TEAM_SEVERITY) */":
          •  LogProblemQueryModel logProblemModel = LogProblemQueryModel.ROOT;
 IDataQuery logProblemQuery = IDataQuery.FACTORY.newInstance(logProblemModel);
 ⋮
 logProblem.getQueryGenerationOptions().QuerysetOracleHints("index({table} {index TEAM_SEVERITY})");
        Parameters:
        oracleHints - the the Oracle-specific hints to be included in the generated SQL for the query; may be null or empty

      • setOmitJPIMapping

        void setOmitJPIMapping(boolean omitJPIMapping)
        Setter for the omitJPIMapping. Note:
        • The system will ignore this flag, being set as true, if the server has not been renamed.
        • If this flag is set on a renamed server having JPI mappings then the system will omit the queryable JPI Mapping table joins during query generation.

        Important: When this flag is set in a data query or item query on a renamed server having JPI mappings:

      • For the data queries selecting the URL attributes, system will now return the "JPI" value for the given attribute & not the "URL" value.
      • For the data or item queries having predicates filtering the URL attributes, system will now expect JPI values to be passed for these filters & not the URL values. Otherwise system will not return correct results.
      • It will be the application's responsibility to do the conversion of JPIs obtained from the IQuery result into URLs if needed. It will also be applicationâ€™s responsibility to only pass the JPI values for the URL attributes used if any in the predicates of IQuery.

        •  Example:
 JPIAuditableQueryModel model = JPIAuditableQueryModel.ROOT;
 IDataQuery dataQuery = IDataQuery.FACTORY.newInstance(model);
 dataQuery.getQueryGenerationOptions().setOmitJPIMapping(true);
Parameters:
omitJPIMapping -

  • setDb2OptimizationGuidelines

    void setDb2OptimizationGuidelines(java.lang.String... optimizationGuidelines)
    Sets optimization guidelines for DB2 (DB2LUW, DB2i, and DB2z). Note:
    • This method applies only when running on DB2. On other DBs, DB2 optimization guidelines are ignored and have no effect.
    • Before you use this method you should be very sure that the optimization guideline(s) you provide will improve performance in all situations likely to be encountered in the field. By using this method you are essentially telling DB2 to ignore what it would have chosen as the best execution plan for the query. It is quite possible to provide an optimization guideline that makes performance significantly worse.
    • For reference, see the Optimization guidelines section in the DB2 Database fundamentals documentation.

    If DB2 optimization guidelines are set then, during query generation, they are included at the appropriate place in the generated SQL as a DB2 optimization guidelines comment ("/* <OPTGUIDELINES>...</OPTGUIDELINES> */"). Each optimization guideline is included after performing any pattern replacements it may include. (See Pattern Replacements in the class description.)

    Examples (using modeled types from com.ibm.team.repository.tests.common/models/RepositoryTestModel.ecore):

    • The following results in optimization guidelines "/* <OPTGUIDELINES><QRYOPT VALUE=\"2\"/><REOPT VALUE=\"ONCE\"/></OPTGUIDELINES> */":
      •  TeamQueryModel teamModel = TeamQueryModel.ROOT;
 AstQuery teamQuery = (AstQuery) IDataQuery.FACTORY.newInstance(teamModel);
 ⋮
 teamQuery.getQueryGenerationOptions().setDb2OptimizationGuidelines("<QRYOPT VALUE=\"2\"/>", "<REOPT VALUE=\"ONCE\"/>");
    • The following results in optimization guidelines "/* <OPTGUIDELINES><IXSCAN TABLE=\"t1\" INDEX=\"TEAM_SEVERITY\"/></OPTGUIDELINES> */":
      •  LogProblemQueryModel logProblemModel = LogProblemQueryModel.ROOT;
 AstQuery logProblemQuery = (AstQuery)IDataQuery.FACTORY.newInstance(logProblemModel);
 ⋮
 teamQuery.getQueryGenerationOptions().setDb2OptimizationGuidelines("<IXSCAN TABLE=\"{table}\" INDEX=\"{index TEAM_SEVERITY}\"/>");

  • setBaselinePattern

    void setBaselinePattern(IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern baselinePattern)
    Sets the IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern. Note that calling this method has an effect only if the relevant query is a) for a configuration-aware type, and b) is actually subsequently executed in the context of a baseline. If the query is not for a configuration-aware type or is executed in the context of some other type of configuration (e.g., a stream) then any IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern set by this method will be silently ignored.

    Important: In general, you should call this method conditionally based on the specific DB you are running on. For example, if you have a query that performs well on Oracle but poorly on DB2 then you should call this method only when running on DB2. A setting that makes a query perform better on one DB could make the same query perform worse on a different DB.

    Parameters:
    baselinePattern - a IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern
    Throws:
    java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if baselinePattern is null
    See Also:
    IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern
